	<body>
		<outline text="July 2021" type="calendarMonth" name="july2021" >
			<outline text="July 21" type="calendarDay" name="21" >
				<outline text="How misinformation sets some people up to die.  1/2

&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.al.com/news/2021/07/im-sorry-but-its-too-late-alabama-doctor-on-treating-unvaccinated-dying-covid-patients.html&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt; https://t.co/633RsZVAfi" type="tweet" created="Wed, 21 Jul 2021 13:46:36 GMT" tweetId="1417843453078159361" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417843453078159361" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
					<outline text="How misinformation sets some people up to die.  2/2 &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417843459906543619/photo/1&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Wed, 21 Jul 2021 13:46:37 GMT" tweetId="1417843459906543619" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417843459906543619" inReplyToId="1417843453078159361" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
					</outline>
				<outline text="“Pandemic of the unvaccinated”

This term, which is probably
as-rhetorical-as-it-is-factual,

aims to persuade the unvaccinated,

but it may cloud the understanding of the vaccinated,

who are, I think, not made safe by the vaccine
but instead gain better odds in the fight." type="tweet" created="Wed, 21 Jul 2021 13:17:32 GMT" tweetId="1417836138203688965" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417836138203688965" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
					<outline text="That is my current understanding, anyway." type="tweet" created="Wed, 21 Jul 2021 13:17:32 GMT" tweetId="1417836139411648512" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417836139411648512" inReplyToId="1417836138203688965" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
					</outline>
				<outline text="With Truman’s diary entries and other reports, Greg Mitchell’s blog posts here trace the thinking that preceded the decision to devastate two Japanese cities using the atomic bomb.

&lt;a href=&quot;https://gregmitchellwriter.blogspot.com/2021/07/countdown-to-hiroshima-july-15-1945.html&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Wed, 21 Jul 2021 11:24:56 GMT" tweetId="1417807801020207104" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417807801020207104" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 20" type="calendarDay" name="20" >
				<outline text="A corporate officer from the region, musing on the subject of hiring our university's graduates, saw two approaches to schooling young people:

&quot;We can train your graduates if you have already educated them,&quot; he said, &quot;but we can't educate them if you have only trained them.&quot;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 20 Jul 2021 22:04:41 GMT" tweetId="1417606411882803201" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417606411882803201" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Might be true:

If you can't talk usefully to generalists about your expertise, you are not a proper expert." type="tweet" created="Tue, 20 Jul 2021 21:59:02 GMT" tweetId="1417604989803970562" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417604989803970562" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 19" type="calendarDay" name="19" >
				<outline text="In New Jersey, in 1993, I bought a black felt hat with a leather band. This hat had the widest brim in the shop.

Later, in Colorado, I bought a brown felt hat just like it, band and all, the hat with the narrowest brim in that shop.

Except for color, they were the same hat. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417211021224206337/photo/1&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 19:53:32 GMT" tweetId="1417211021224206337" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417211021224206337" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Countdown to Hiroshima: &quot;Every year at this time I trace the final days leading to the first use of the atomic bomb against two cities, Hiroshima and Nagasaki, in August 1945.&quot; &lt;a href=&quot;https://gregmitchellwriter.blogspot.com/2021/07/countdown-to-hiroshima-july-15-1945.html&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 14:34:10 GMT" tweetId="1417130650260447249" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417130650260447249" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="I was told by a dean once that a university is made up of three groups of people, students, faculty, and administration, and that whenever two of those groups really want something that thing will happen." type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 14:02:25 GMT" tweetId="1417122657556963331" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417122657556963331" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Once upon a time, Bloglines made it easy to read new postings on site after site and on topic after topic of your own choosing. Automated standing searches, ready to read each time you opened Bloglines in the browser. Not the only way, but a notable one. &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloglines&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 13:59:22 GMT" tweetId="1417121892465524744" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417121892465524744" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
					<outline text="The automation was a real virtue. Still, it was a sort of broadcast mechanism, rather than a tool for shaping working groups. Long ago, semaphore showed how to move messages through a planned, prepared network, for a purpose. We can't readily create that semaphore effect, can we?" type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 15:14:54 GMT" tweetId="1417140902124982278" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417140902124982278" inReplyToId="1417121892465524744" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
					</outline>
				<outline text="How wealth moves in the U.S.A.
&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2021/07/16/us-is-growing-more-unequal-thats-harmful-fixable/&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt; https://t.co/WsDK7upoT2" type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 13:41:24 GMT" tweetId="1417117368552132610" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417117368552132610" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="If Truman knew that the Japanese emperor had asked for the war to end in July, more than two weeks before Hiroshima, well, that makes it harder than ever for me to justify the atomic bombing of two populated cities in August. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/GregMitch/status/1417108436714655756&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Mon, 19 Jul 2021 13:14:37 GMT" tweetId="1417110631380099076" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1417110631380099076" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 18" type="calendarDay" name="18" >
				<outline text="I wonder:

When planes had smoking sections, by mid-flight the whole interior smelled of cigarettes. Has aircraft ventilation changed since then?

Cigarette smoke moved throughout the cabin. Should we now assume that viruses are everywhere in the cabin? I don’t have an answer." type="tweet" created="Sun, 18 Jul 2021 22:33:34 GMT" tweetId="1416888907359264778" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416888907359264778" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Every night, somebody stays up late plotting how to hollow out the democracy just a little more. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416755837477982209/photo/1&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sun, 18 Jul 2021 13:44:48 GMT" tweetId="1416755837477982209" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416755837477982209" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Monarch egg on the front yard milkweed yesterday. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416735574665347077/photo/1&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sun, 18 Jul 2021 12:24:17 GMT" tweetId="1416735574665347077" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416735574665347077" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 17" type="calendarDay" name="17" >
				<outline text="A century ago, health inspector Dr. Peter Bryce tried to get Canada to attend to the 25% or higher death rates, often from tuberculosis, at the residential schools, where the most rudimentary health practices were not widely employed. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cbc.ca/radio/unreserved/exploring-the-past-finding-connections-in-little-known-indigenous-history-1.5531914/pushed-out-and-silenced-how-one-doctor-was-punished-for-speaking-out-about-residential-schools-1.5534953&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sat, 17 Jul 2021 14:17:00 GMT" tweetId="1416401553867563008" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416401553867563008" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
					<outline text="Bryce’s blunt report also contained subtle clues about the emotional cost to the students. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/kensmith/status/1416404679362334728?s=21&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sat, 17 Jul 2021 14:32:28 GMT" tweetId="1416405447381241857" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1416405447381241857" inReplyToId="1416401553867563008" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 13" type="calendarDay" name="13" >
				<outline text="Thread on Adorno's view of the essay. First, what he's not talking about. Not talking about the school essay, which is for training and indoctrinating young people and is often boring to writer and reader." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:09 GMT" tweetId="1415018730040532993" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018730040532993" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
					<outline text="And Adorno is not talking about the academic article, which is an expert talking narrowly to a handful of colleagues in a lingo not meant to be useful to any others." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:10 GMT" tweetId="1415018732028579843" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018732028579843" inReplyToId="1415018730040532993" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
						<outline text="Last I heard, there were two English translations of &quot;Essay as Form&quot; by Theodor Adorno. I'll use and link to the one I have at hand. It's a real pain to read this piece. So what's useful in it? Let me rephrase the question:" type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:10 GMT" tweetId="1415018733593153547" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018733593153547" inReplyToId="1415018732028579843" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
							<outline text="What's useful for a writer who cares about creativity and knows the personal and social energy of writing for others who respond--as we saw in a new way twenty years ago in blogging? For writers who want reading and writing to be part of the lifeblood of self and society." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:10 GMT" tweetId="1415018735312723973" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018735312723973" inReplyToId="1415018733593153547" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
								<outline text="Two sentences from the end, Adorno says, &quot;The essay's innermost formal law is heresy.&quot;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:11 GMT" tweetId="1415018737187627008" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018737187627008" inReplyToId="1415018735312723973" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
									<outline text="He means that in our minds and in society all ideas, even the best ones, calcify, and so to move ahead creative people have to break things open. They have to speak against the society's docile common sense, where they see fit, where they feel the urgency." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:11 GMT" tweetId="1415018738726932480" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018738726932480" inReplyToId="1415018737187627008" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
										<outline text="He ends by saying, &quot;Through violating this orthodoxy of thought, something becomes visible which it is orthodoxy's secret and enduring aim to keep invisible.&quot;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:12 GMT" tweetId="1415018739939127301" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018739939127301" inReplyToId="1415018738726932480" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
											<outline text="The status quo is served by the calcified language, the taken-for-granted concepts. Life, however, is served by heresy against those crusty ornaments that were once life-giving but are no longer." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:12 GMT" tweetId="1415018741071503361" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018741071503361" inReplyToId="1415018739939127301" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
												<outline text="Can academics do this kind of work? Yes, but if they only use their shop talk and only write for readers who are their clones, they rarely get around to it. Academics usually gain their authority from shop talk and institutional roles and their sheepskin." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:12 GMT" tweetId="1415018743579750414" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018743579750414" inReplyToId="1415018741071503361" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
													<outline text="Writers can get their authority other ways. They can get it by choosing what they write about in such a way that they expose something new in it rather than repeat what common sense already knows about it." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:13 GMT" tweetId="1415018745702014976" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018745702014976" inReplyToId="1415018743579750414" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
														<outline text="Maybe they put together historical examples they we have never thought about as being related." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:13 GMT" tweetId="1415018746868113408" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018746868113408" inReplyToId="1415018745702014976" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
															<outline text="Then they do the work to notice something about the juxtaposition that common sense doesn't care about. In that way they challenge and refresh and extend the common sense of their society." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:13 GMT" tweetId="1415018747945967619" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018747945967619" inReplyToId="1415018746868113408" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
																<outline text="And they get their authority by repeating this creative act over and over again. Not by their job or their diploma or their shop talk. People who like the feeling of being awake notice writers who can do this and come back to them." type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:14 GMT" tweetId="1415018749258866692" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018749258866692" inReplyToId="1415018747945967619" tweetUserName="KenSmith" >
																	<outline text="So, Adorno is correct. The innermost trait of a fine essay is an act of heresy it commits against something calcified in the common sense of the society. Pdf link here. &lt;a href=&quot;https://web.english.upenn.edu/~cavitch/pdf-library/Adorno_EssayAsForm.pdf&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:42:14 GMT" tweetId="1415018750357684228" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1415018750357684228" inReplyToId="1415018749258866692" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
																	</outline>
																</outline>
															</outline>
														</outline>
													</outline>
												</outline>
											</outline>
										</outline>
									</outline>
								</outline>
							</outline>
						</outline>
					</outline>
				<outline text="“An unequal society is violent every day.” Brief thread. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/rosebellk/status/1414924899269890066&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 15:53:02 GMT" tweetId="1414976168885882886" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1414976168885882886" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="The violence in a revolt shows vividly on news screens; the simmering, demeaning violence that precedes and provokes it makes a less dramatic broadcast, if it is, if it can be, broadcast at all. Thread. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/rosebellk/status/1414845583525826562&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 13 Jul 2021 11:03:33 GMT" tweetId="1414903316975431685" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1414903316975431685" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 11" type="calendarDay" name="11" >
				<outline text="Our powers our multiplied, not added... &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1413871853362454529&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sun, 11 Jul 2021 13:31:19 GMT" tweetId="1414215728962678784" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1414215728962678784" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="...moving to a land where most failed to hear the urgency of samizdat... &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/ilya_poet/status/1413946559318962177&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sun, 11 Jul 2021 07:56:28 GMT" tweetId="1414131460156575747" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1414131460156575747" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 8" type="calendarDay" name="08" >
				<outline text="Judging by a three-minute teaser, gutless sycophant Bill O’Reilly will be lobbing softballs on tv tonight to a loser ex-President on his best behavior, answering coyly and vapidly, and desperate to get back in front of a public which by the tens of millions despises him." type="tweet" created="Thu, 08 Jul 2021 20:33:33 GMT" tweetId="1413234823188123650" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1413234823188123650" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Mergers disadvantage workers. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/upshotnyt/status/1412837336833040387&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt; https://t.co/l59RuzYnvh" type="tweet" created="Thu, 08 Jul 2021 15:36:02 GMT" tweetId="1413159952458321930" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1413159952458321930" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="This article’s detailed introduction to Big Ag, pollution, and politics in Iowa is frankly disgusting. Powerhouse work by Paul Brennan. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/austinfrerick/status/1413142947156004869&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Thu, 08 Jul 2021 15:01:49 GMT" tweetId="1413151342479044609" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1413151342479044609" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="In 1979, my first spring in Iowa, the tap water in Iowa City came for a time to reek of chlorine as, I gathered, the animal waste and fertilizer thawed from the farmland, filled the streams and rivers, and taxed the water treatment plants. I hear Iowa rivers are worse now. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/austinfrerick/status/1413142947156004869&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Thu, 08 Jul 2021 14:41:25 GMT" tweetId="1413146205782114309" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1413146205782114309" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="A farmer’s lifelong web of observation, reflection, and insight, expressed with modest urgency, lacking perhaps any other way to share it. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/hawhillfarm/status/1413112394809761795&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Thu, 08 Jul 2021 14:32:25 GMT" tweetId="1413143941239562252" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1413143941239562252" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Potent, insightful verb here.

My father’s fillet knife was the sharpest, the most wicked-looking knife, used for quickly taking the choicest parts of a bass for cooking. Toss the scraps back into the lake.

Citizens grow active or what they care about gets filleted by others. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/hawhillfarm/status/1347849513323659264&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Thu, 08 Jul 2021 14:28:31 GMT" tweetId="1413142962138083328" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1413142962138083328" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 7" type="calendarDay" name="07" >
				<outline text="“So what! Finders keepers! Shut up!” 

Comedian James Acaster explores some rhetoric the powerful use to justify keeping stolen wealth.

&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x73PkUvArJY&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Wed, 07 Jul 2021 13:08:38 GMT" tweetId="1412760468767260672" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1412760468767260672" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="University of Notre Dame failed to reshape a dorm’s culture:

 “..significant vandalism over many years within and beyond the building..demonstrated disrespect for University officials, deliberate disregard for University COVID-19 testing protocols..” &lt;a href=&quot;https://magazine.nd.edu/stories/zahm-hall-ends-its-84-year-run-as-a-traditional-residence-hall/&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Wed, 07 Jul 2021 12:59:21 GMT" tweetId="1412758135299883010" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1412758135299883010" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 6" type="calendarDay" name="06" >
				<outline text="Story I heard.

Gadamer, nearing 100 years of age, frail at the podium, lectured in Boston. Finishing, he offered to take questions.

“Who will refute me?” he asked.

No hands raised.

“Very well,” he said, “I shall refute myself.”

And he explored weaknesses in his argument." type="tweet" created="Tue, 06 Jul 2021 17:23:28 GMT" tweetId="1412462212489359360" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1412462212489359360" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="Story I heard.

Gadamer, nearing 100 years of age, frail at the podium, lectured in Boston. Finishing, he offered to take questions.

“Who will refute me?” he asked.

No hands were raised.

“Very well,” he said, “I shall refute myself.”

And explored weaknesses in his argument." type="tweet" created="Tue, 06 Jul 2021 17:21:55 GMT" tweetId="1412461822683275267" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1412461822683275267" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 5" type="calendarDay" name="05" >
				<outline text="In 1852, Frederick Douglass spoke about what the 4th of July meant to an enslaved person. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/edgeofsports/status/1411677339893780480&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt; https://t.co/jng08n7vs2" type="tweet" created="Tue, 06 Jul 2021 00:04:52 GMT" tweetId="1412200838727151618" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1412200838727151618" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 2" type="calendarDay" name="02" >
				<outline text="Note to self. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1411127471186059265/photo/1&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Sat, 03 Jul 2021 00:59:41 GMT" tweetId="1411127471186059265" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1411127471186059265" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="A country in need of a shared narrative, an honorable narrative with places in it for everyone. A country that doesn’t tell its best stories richly, accurately, or well. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/nytdavidbrooks/status/1410790282354958337&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Fri, 02 Jul 2021 11:11:14 GMT" tweetId="1410918984925560837" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1410918984925560837" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 1" type="calendarDay" name="01" >
				<outline text="“Conspiracy practices – the methods by which true conspiracies such as gerrymandering, or the debt industry, or mass surveillance are realized – are almost always overshadowed by conspiracy theories: those malevolent falsehoods...” —Edward Snowden. https://t.co/iXFoNb7Skq" type="tweet" created="Thu, 01 Jul 2021 13:53:16 GMT" tweetId="1410597374401998853" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1410597374401998853" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
				<outline text="A sample paragraph:

In 1979, an Exxon study said that burning fossil fuels “will cause dramatic environmental effects” in the coming decades. “The potential problem is great and urgent,” it concluded. https://t.co/W153z1IlU0" type="tweet" created="Thu, 01 Jul 2021 09:09:01 GMT" tweetId="1410525839138213890" urltweet="https://twitter.com/KenSmith/status/1410525839138213890" tweetUserName="KenSmith" />
